{"cursor":"3351","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox MLB player |name=Otto Hess |position=Pitcher |image=Otto Hess.jpg\n|bats=Left |throws=Left |birth_date= |birth_place=Bern, Switzerland |death_date=\n|death_place=Tucson, Arizona, United States |debutdate= August 3 |debutyear=\n1902 |debutteam= Cleveland Bronchos |finaldate=June 13 |finalyear=1915\n|finalteam=Boston Braves |stat1label=Pitching record |stat1value=70â90\n|stat2label=Earned run average |stat2value=2.98 |stat3label=Strikeouts\n|stat3value=580 |teams=\n* Cleveland Bronchos/Naps (â)\n* Boston Braves (â) |highlights= *World Series champion: 1914\n  }} 'Otto C. Hess' (October 10, 1878 â February 25, 1926) born in Bern,\n  Switzerland was a pitcher for the Cleveland Bronchos/Cleveland Naps (1902 and\n  1904â08) and Boston Braves (1912â15).\n\nIn 1914, Hess was a member of the Braves team that went from last place to\nfirst place in two months, becoming the first team to win a pennant after\nbeing in last place on the Fourth of July. [http://books.google.com/books-\n?id=aS0DAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA84&dq=hank+gowdy+baseball+digest&cd=3#v=onepage&q=hank%-\n20gowdy%20baseball%20digest&f=false How Losing an Exhibition Sparked Miracle\nBraves, by Joseph M. Overfield, Baseball Digest, May 1961, Vol. 20, No. 4,\nISSN 0005-609X] He is the first person born in Switzerland to play Major\nLeague Baseball.\n\nIn 10 seasons he had a 70â90 win-loss record in 198 games, with 165 games\nstarted, 129 complete games, 18 shutouts, 5 saves, 1,418 innings pitched, 1,355\nhits allowed, 663 runs allowed, 25 home runs allowed, 448 walks allowed, 580\nstrikeouts, 83 hit batsmen, 38 wild pitches and a 2.98 ERA. He died in Tucson,\nArizona at the age of 47.\n","linknr":209,"url":"Otto_Hess_(pitcher)","recorded":1375076794,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Otto_Hess&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Otto_Hess&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/